[6] Australia (Western Australia): travel associated
Date: Tue 3 Apr 2018 11:00 AM
Source: Canning Times [edited]
https://www.communitynews.com.au/canning-times/news/fourth-wa-resident-reported-with-case-of-measles-acquired-overseas/


A 4th case of measles acquired overseas has been reported in a WA [Western Australia] resident.

The cases are unrelated, but all 4 infected residents were diagnosed within a 10-day period in March [2018]. 2 travellers were infected in Bali, one in Malaysia, and the other person was most likely infected in Thailand or Malaysia.

As a result of the infections, people could potentially have been exposed to measles at healthcare facilities including Bentley, Royal Perth, and Joondalup Hospitals, GP surgeries and pharmacies, and other parts of Perth including Perth Airport.

Doctors are on alert for secondary measles cases that could present up until the middle of this month [April 2018].

The spike prompted the Department of Health on 24 Mar 2018 to urge people to check and update their vaccinations prior to overseas travels from Perth.

It is recommended that the measles vaccine be considered for people travelling overseas who were born after 1965 and who do not have documentation of having had 2 doses of measles vaccine.

There may be an ongoing increased risk of measles infection in Bali.

One confirmed locally acquired case of mumps was also reported recently, with the source of the infection unknown.

[Byline: Jaime Shurmer]

